<%#
  The session card. `password` is a per-session random string, generated in
  before.sh.erb and persisted by OnDemand in the session's connection.yml (mode
  0600, readable only by its owner) -- so it needs no plumbing here beyond being
  named. There is no password field on the launch form because the user does not
  choose it.

  The Connect button signs in from scratch on EVERY click. That is the whole
  recovery path: if RStudio ever shows its own sign-in page (a "Sign out", or an
  idle timeout beyond --auth-timeout-minutes), the user just comes back here and
  clicks Connect again. Nothing needs to be remembered.

  It has to SAY so, though. Previously it did not, and the credentials were
  invisible -- so a user locked out at RStudio's own login screen had a password
  box and no password. That dead end is the most plausible reason someone once
  hard-coded the password to the literal string "password", which let any user on
  the cluster into any session. Showing the credentials here removes the reason
  to ever do that again. It leaks nothing: this card renders only on its owner's
  dashboard, from a file only they can read.
-%>
<script>
  document.cookie = "csrf-token=<%= csrf_token %>; path=/rnode/<%= host %>/<%= port %>; secure";
</script>
<form action="/rnode/<%= host %>/<%= port %>/auth-do-sign-in" method="post" target="_blank">
  <input type="hidden" name="username" value="<%= ENV["USER"] %>">
  <input type="hidden" name="password" value="<%= password %>">
  <input type="hidden" name="staySignedIn" value="1">
  <input type="hidden" name="appUri" value="">
  <input type="hidden" name="csrf-token" value="<%= csrf_token %>"/>
  <button class="btn btn-primary" type="submit">
    <i class="fa fa-registered"></i> Connect to RStudio Server
  </button>
</form>

<details style="margin-top:0.75em">
  <summary style="cursor:pointer">Signed out of RStudio? Click here.</summary>
  <div style="margin-top:0.5em">
    <p style="margin-bottom:0.5em">
      Just press <strong>Connect to RStudio Server</strong> again — it signs you
      back in. You never need to type these. They are generated per session and
      only you can see them.
    </p>
    <table class="table table-condensed" style="margin-bottom:0.25em; width:auto">
      <tr>
        <td style="padding-right:1em"><strong>Username</strong></td>
        <td><code><%= ENV["USER"] %></code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td style="padding-right:1em"><strong>Password</strong></td>
        <td><code><%= password %></code></td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <p class="text-muted" style="margin-bottom:0">
      Only if RStudio shows its own sign-in page and the button above will not
      clear it. This password is valid for this session alone and dies with it.
    </p>
  </div>
</details>
